<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0">
    <teiHeader><fileDesc><titleStmt><title>The Ambassador in the Soviet Union (
                        Harriman
                    ) to the Secretary of
                            State</title></titleStmt><sourceDesc><bibl type="frus-volume-id">frus1945v02</bibl><bibl type="frus-document-id">d195</bibl><bibl type="frus-document-number">195</bibl><bibl type="frus-div-subtype">historical-document</bibl></sourceDesc></fileDesc><profileDesc><settingDesc><setting><date notBefore="1945-10-18T08:00:00-05:00" notAfter="1945-10-18T08:00:00-05:00"/></setting></settingDesc></profileDesc></teiHeader><text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1945-10-18T08:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1945-10-18T08:00:00-05:00" n="195" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d195">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00119 Council/10–1845: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Harriman</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-10-18T16:00:00+03:00">October 18, 1945—4 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received October 18—12:20 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>3588. Personal for the Secretary. My 3558, October 16.<note n="13" xml:id="d195fn13">See footnote 11, <ref target="#pg_563">p.
                        563</ref>.</note> Molotov called me to the Kremlin this afternoon and read
                    to me from a message he had received from Stalin. Stalin said he would receive
                    me with pleasure at Sochi where he is on leave in order to receive the message
                    from the President and to discuss it with me. He suggested the 24th, 25th or
                    26th of October. I replied the sooner the better and we settled on October
                    24.</p>
                <pb facs="0577" n="565" xml:id="pg_565"/>
                <p>Molotov has placed a plane at my disposal and I plan to take Page<note n="14" xml:id="d195fn14">Edward Page, First Secretary of Embassy.</note> to
                    interpret and a communications officer so that I can communicate with you
                    through the Embassy if it proves necessary.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Harriman</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
</TEI>
